  "prompt": "Why does the intensity of light become half when a lens is cut horizontally but not if cut perpendicular to principal axis?",
  "response": "To understand this, let's break down the concept of lens cutting and light transmission:\n\n1. Lens Cut Horizontally:\n- When a lens is cut horizontally (parallel to the principal axis), the entire optical path is preserved for each point of the lens.\n- However, the lens area is reduced by half.\n- Since the lens area is reduced, the light-gathering capacity is reduced proportionally.\n- This results in the intensity of light being reduced to half.\n\n2. Lens Cut Perpendicular to Principal Axis:\n- When a lens is cut perpendicular to the principal axis, it essentially creates two identical smaller lenses.\n- Each half of the lens contains the complete focusing capability of the original lens.\n- The entire optical path and curvature are maintained for each half.\n- Therefore, the light transmission and intensity remain unchanged.\n\nKey Points:\n- Area reduction affects light intensity\n- Maintaining optical path and curvature preserves light transmission\n- Horizontal cutting reduces light-gathering capacity\n- Perpendicular cutting preserves optical properties\n\nThis difference occurs because of how light propagates through different lens cuts, demonstrating the importance of lens geometry in optical systems.",
